attributes.title: Development of a cell free split luciferase biochemical assay as a tool for screening for inhibitors of challenging protein-protein interaction targets, Figures
attributes.description: Figures of the: "Development of a cell free split luciferase biochemical assay as a tool for screening for inhibitors of challenging protein-protein interaction targets" paper

q3.value: Targeting the interaction of proteins with weak binding affinities or low solubility represents a particular challenge for drug screening. The NanoLuc Binary Technology (NanoBiT) was originally developed to detect protein-protein interactions in live mammalian cells. Here we report the successful translation of the NanoBit cellular assay into a biochemical, cell-free format using mammalian cell lysates. We show that the assay is suitable for the detection of both strong and weak protein interactions such as those involving the binding of RAS oncoproteins to either RAF or Phosphoinositide 3-kinase (PI3K) effectors respectively, and that it is also effective for the study of poorly soluble protein domains such as the RAS binding domain of PI3K. Furthermore, the RAS interaction assay is sensitive and responds to both strong and weak RAS inhibitors. Our data show that the assay is robust, reproducible, cost-effective, and can be adapted for small and large-scale screening approaches. The NanoBit Biochemical Assay offers an attractive tool for drug screening against challenging protein-protein interaction targets, including the interaction of RAS with PI3K.

q4.value: In this study we attempted to translate the NanoBiT cellular assay to  the NanoBiT Biochemical Assay (NBBA). We show that the NBBA is a simple and robust assay and is sensitive to detect weak and strong protein interactions (PPI). Furthermore, we show that the NBBA is also sensitive to strong and weak RAS inhibitors, which makes it suitable for drug screening. Finally, the NBBA is suitable for small and large scale PPI and drug screening.

q5.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value: In our study we aimed to show that the NBBA is a new and reliable assay for detecting a PPI previously shown to occur by other methods. We used the example of the RAS/p110 alpha that interacts with RAS with an affinity of about 3µM and p110 beta that does not interact with RAS as a negative control. In our study, we show that the NBBA detected the interaction of RAS with p110 alpha but not with p110 beta. These experiment involved two groups of lysate and each concentration point was repeated 3 times (n=3).

q10.value: Registration following analysis of the data

question.value:
No human subjects were involved in this purely biochemical study. 
All the data was collected from the plate reader PheraStar FSX Detection System (BMG Labtech). The data was collected over 50min with a read every 5min. The data was then analysed on Excel program to generate the mean,  the standard deviation and data plotting.  The source of all samples were from mammalian cell line lysates.

q13.value: In our biochemical studies, we ensured that there is at least 12-14 points of titration and each point has been repeated for 3 times (n=3).

question.value: The key variable that has been measured in this study the relative luminescence among samples in each experiment.
Data points were combined into an arithmetic mean with standard deviation at all titration points.
We used SEM (standard error mean) as a mathematical model in all experiments.

attributes.title: RCT - Messages to promote plant-based eating

q1.value: Advocating plant-based eating – Which messages work best for whom, and why?

q2.value: João Graça, Cristina Godinho, John Hoeks, Marta Matos, Lúcia Campos, David Guedes

q3.value: There have been increasing calls for triggering and sustaining transitions toward reduced meat consumption and increased plant-based eating, due to global health and sustainability concerns. However, encouraging meat curtailment has been shown to have starkly different results in different consumers: some may easily be willing to change their diet, while others may become heavily entrenched in meat-eating justifications. Drawing on a stage theory of behavior change (i.e., the HAPA model), this RCT will test the effects of different types of message content for different consumers, and shed light on the psychological mechanisms that explain these effects. The findings of this project will provide evidence on which types of message work best for whom and why, in order to promote transitions to more plant-based diets.

q4.value: The main hypothesis is that exposure to a theory-based message targeting motivational and volitional predictors of behavior change (vs control) will lead to increases in predictors of adherence to a plant-based diet. In addition, messages matched to the stage of consumers (i.e., motivation message for non-intenders and capacitation message for intenders) will be more effective than messages that are mismatched.

q5.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: For studies that involve human subjects, they will not know the treatment group to which they have been assigned.

question.value: A factorial (between-subjects) design will be used with 2 (stage of change: non-intenders vs. intenders) x 4 (message condition: motivation vs. capacitation vs. combination vs. control), with repeated measures (baseline/post-message exposure, one week later).

q9.value: A stratified randomization will be used, i.e., non-intenders and intenders will be randomly assigned to one of four conditions. Both non-intenders and intenders will be equally distributed by the conditions, so as to have an approximately equal number of participants in the same stage assigned to each message condition.

q10.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: Participant recruitment and data collection will be outsourced to a marketing research institute. People from a panel of three different countries in two continents (United States of America, Portugal and the Netherlands) will be invited to participate. To be included in the study, participants will have to be aged 20 to 35 years old, reside in the United States of America, Portugal or the Netherlands, and speak the native language of the country they reside in. Participants who do not comply with these criteria will not be included in the sample. Before starting the survey, participants will be asked to complete a consent form and two questions to determine their stage of change (i.e., intenders; non-intenders), and will be then randomly allocated into one of four different message conditions. Actors (i.e., people who eat more than six plant-based meals per week, on average) will not be considered eligible for the study. One week after filling the survey, participants will be asked to fill the same measures and their responses will be paired using a unique anonymized identifier.

q13.value: Using G*POWER 3.1.9.2 (Faul et al., 2009), a sample size of n=364 will be required in each country to give 80% power to detect a statistically significant difference at α=0.05 through repeated measures ANOVA, if an effect size of f=0.1 or higher is observed (Godinho et al., 2016) and inflated by 30%, given the possibility of drop-out. Thus, at least 1092 people are expected to participate in the study.

question.value: Message content will be manipulated: motivation message, capacitation message, combination (motivation and capacitation) message, or control. Message content was developed addressing the theoretical constructs posited to be relevant in the HAPA model (Schwarzer et al., 2008), and framed as to support the basic psychological needs proposed by the Self-Determination Theory (Ryan & Deci, 2000). The final version of the messages was developed and adjusted based on a pilot study with samples from the three countries.
Repeated measures ANOVAs will be used to capture the effect of the messages on predictors of adherence to a plant-based diet (see Measured Variables section), among intenders and non-intenders.

q23.value: As the data collection process will be outsourced (panel data), we do not expect to have missing data.

q24.value: We expect that a set of variables relevant for the target behavior (e.g., psychological reactance, affect, threat construal, meat attachment, attitudes, prevalence of plant-based eating in social network) may be related with the impact of the different messages (motivation, capacitation, combination) in the different groups of consumers (intenders, non-intenders).

attributes.title: Memory attack by semantic mediator: causing retroactive interference via Deese-Roediger-McDermott lists

q1.value: Semantic similarity and retroactive interference with delay between phase 1 and 2

q3.value: Here we will repeat the same paradigm as in the above studies, except this time instituting a delay between phase 1 and 2. For context, the initial two studies had all of the phases back to back in time, with one of them swapping the order to investigate proactive rather than retroactive interference. The last study instituted a delay between phase 2 and phase 3 to examine whether our interference effect lasted after a longer delay of an hour. However, we did not find a significant effect. Here we will explore whether our phenomenon is more of a retrieval effect or possibly whether the interference is shorter lasting. We predict we will find a significant interference effect.

q4.value: Like in our first previous studies, we hypothesize that semantic similarity in a retroactive interference context will impair spatial memory retrieval, this time with a one hour delay before test. We will power this study to the same degree (N=112; see previous versions on this page).

q5.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value: This is a within-subject design. All subjects will be exposed to the experimental (related words shown in Phase 2) and control (related words not shown in Phase 2) conditions.

q10.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: We will use undergraduate students taking this for course credit or extra credit. We hope to be done with the study by the end of February 2020, depending on how quickly we can reach 112 subjects.

q13.value: N=112 based on a power analysis from a previous study. There may or may not be more subjects, depending on how quickly and how many sign-ups there are at once, but we will stop recruiting once N=112 is reached.

q14.value: This is an identical power analysis from the previous study to reach beta=0.8 at alpha=0.05.

q15.value: We will stop collecting sign-ups once N = 112 is reached.

question.value: We are manipulating whether or not spatial memories (for words) will have semantically related content presented in a prior phase.

These measures are identical to the previous versions. For the main finding, we will measure spatial memory accuracy based on whether or centrally presented words are dragged to the correct, learned location. We will also measure recognition as in the previous version.

We will use t-tests to address the main question of spatial recall and recognition, as in the previous experiments and the current version of the code. We will also run a bootstrapping procedure using backward and forward associative strength to look at the effects of these variables on our main effects of spatial impairment, as in the previous experiments and the current version of the code.

q21.value: We will make inferences based on the P-value of the t-test at alpha = 0.05.

q24.value: If we do find an effect of semantic similarity, we will explore the role of awareness of the relatedness of the words in phase 1 and 2, as in previous versions. We will also look at backward and forward associative strength, as mentioned above.

q3.value:
In the studies by Bernstein and Harley (2007) participants identified faces of celebrities at varying levels of image blurriness (baseline phase), and in a subsequent memory phase adjusted the blurriness to the level at which they recognized the face before. The authors manipulated processing fluency, such that faces in the memory phase were presented either upright or inverted. The consistently higher levels of blurriness in the second (memory) phase (compared to the first baseline phase) were interpreted as evidence of the visual hindsight bias. 

In the present study, we replicate the setup with new stimuli, appropriate for Austrian (German-speaking) population. Together with the results from two preceding studies, we assume that the presentation of the whole blurriness range at baseline (instead of just stopping when the participant guessed right) is necessary to reproduce the visual hindsight bias. We thus administer the task of Study 2 in Bernstein and Harley (2007) in two groups, one group will see the whole blurriness range, and for the other group the presentation of each face will stop as soon the celebrity is recognized (partial blurriness range).

q4.value:
(1) In the memory phase of group 1 (whole blurriness range), participants will report to have recognized the celebrities at a higher blurriness level than in the baseline phase (visual hindsight bias).

(2) This difference will be higher if faces in the memory test are presented upright than if they are inverted.

(3) In group 2, we expect similar results to our preceding studies. For upright faces in the memory test, there will be no significant differences in blurriness compared to baseline.

(4) For inverted faces, we predict a reverse hindsight bias: blurriness in the memory phase will be significantly lower than in baseline.

q5.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: Personnel who interact directly with the study subjects (either human or non-human subjects) will not be aware of the assigned treatments. (Commonly known as “double blind”)

question.value:
Mixed factors 2-factorial design:

1) within subjects factor: stimuls type in memory test with two levels: upright vs. inverted. 
2) between subjects factor: blurriness range at baseline with two levels: full blurriness range vs. partial blurriness range (face presentation stops as soon as recognized)

Stimuli. 
Famous celebrity images were selected from the Internet Movie Database (IMDB, 2014) and from direct google search, including only images with (1) a steadfast gaze towards the camera, (2) an emotionally neutral facial expression, and (3) a gray and empty background. Finally, all images were transformed to black-and-white. We compiled images of 50 celebrities. 

Procedure. 
Stimulus presentation in the baseline phase started with the most blurred image, followed by images with decreasing level of blurriness presented every 400 ms up to the clear, unblurred image. Participants were instructed to press the space bar, as soon as they recognized the actor shown, and to type either the name, famous role or movie the celebrity is known for. In total, each participant saw images of 30 celebrities, that were randomly selected from our data base of 50 images. 
In the full blurriness range group, stimulus presentation continued up to the fully clear image after participants gave their answer, and participants could revise their answer.  Finally, participants were given accuracy feedback. In the partial blurriness range group, participants were given accuracy feedback immediately following their first response without further stimulus presentation.

Memory Test.
On each trial of the memory test, participants saw a clear image of an actor for 2 seconds, followed by the most blurred image. Then they were asked to adjust the blurriness of the image (using the left/right arrow keys) to match the blurriness at which they recognized the actor in the preceding baseline phase. Only actors that were correctly identified in the baseline phase were presented in the memory phase. For each participant, a randomly selected half of these images were presented upright and the other half inverted.

All participants completed two warm-up trials at the beginning of each phase. 

The experimental task was setup in OpenSesame and the corresonding files (including all instructions and stimuli) are provided on osf.

q9.value: N = 56 participants will be randomly assigned to either full blurriness range (group 1) or the partial blurriness range (group 2) at baseline. Stimuli in the memory phase will be presented in random order.

q10.value: Registration prior to any human observation of the data

question.value: Participants are students of psychology and will receive partial course credit for participation.

q14.value: Sample size for the direct replication group 1 was determined using a priori power analysis with the software GPower for a dependent samples t-test (one-tailed), alpha = .05, beta = .10, and Cohen’s d = .57 calculated from the corresponding result in experiment 2 of B&H (2007, [t(41) = 3.68]). The protocol is available on osf. In order to have equal group sizes, we plan to test 28 participants in each group (56 total).

question.value:
1) Blurriness range at baseline: 

We manipulated the presentation of celebrity images in two levels: either upright face presentation or inverted (upside down).

(1) Main DV
The main DV is the level of blurriness (1 to 50) at which participants recognize a celebrity in the baseline phase and the blurriness at which they remember to have recognized each celebrity in the memory phase. The 50 blurriness levels represent one original, unblurred image and 49 additional images with increasing degrees of blurriness that were created by applying a Gauss-filter to the original image, with sigma increasing from .5 to 24.5 in .5 steps. 

(2) Covariates
Additionally, we asses (1) the number of movies/series per month, and, (2) the to expected number of celebrities a person will recognize out of 30.

Direct Replication Group 1: full blurriness range

We will use two one-sample t-tests (one-tailed) for the blurriness level difference between baseline and memory phase, one for inverted and one for upright faces. Compared to the baseline, the blurriness level in the memory phase should be significantly higher in both conditions. Additionally, we will use a dependent samples t-test between upright and inverted faces conditions (as used in the power analysis). We expect the difference in blurriness to baseline is significantly higher in the upright than in the inverted condition.

Group 2: partial blurriness range

We will use two one-sample t-tests (one-tailed) for the blurriness level difference between baseline and memory phase, one for inverted and one for upright faces. For inverted faces the blurriness level will be significantly lower in memory than in baseline. For upright faces, we expect no significant differences between memory and baseline.

Memory Test.
On each trial of the memory test, participants saw a clear image of an actor for 2 seconds, followed by the most blurred image. Then they were asked to adjust the blurriness of the image (using the left/right arrow keys) to match the blurriness at which they recognized the actor in the preceding baseline phase. Only actors that were correctly identified in the baseline phase were presented in the memory phase. For each participant, a randomly selected half of these images were presented upright and the other half inverted.

All participants completed two warm-up trials at the beginning of each phase. 

The experimental task was setup in OpenSesame and the corresonding files (including all instructions and stimuli) are provided on osf.
registration_responses.q12.question: Participants are students of psychology and will receive partial course credit for participation.
registration_responses.q16.question:
1) Blurriness range at baseline: 

We manipulated the presentation of celebrity images in two levels: either upright face presentation or inverted (upside down).
registration_responses.q17.question:
(1) Main DV
The main DV is the level of blurriness (1 to 50) at which participants recognize a celebrity in the baseline phase and the blurriness at which they remember to have recognized each celebrity in the memory phase. The 50 blurriness levels represent one original, unblurred image and 49 additional images with increasing degrees of blurriness that were created by applying a Gauss-filter to the original image, with sigma increasing from .5 to 24.5 in .5 steps. 

(2) Covariates
Additionally, we asses (1) the number of movies/series per month, and, (2) the to expected number of celebrities a person will recognize out of 30.
registration_responses.q19.question:
Direct Replication Group 1: full blurriness range

We will use two one-sample t-tests (one-tailed) for the blurriness level difference between baseline and memory phase, one for inverted and one for upright faces. Compared to the baseline, the blurriness level in the memory phase should be significantly higher in both conditions. Additionally, we will use a dependent samples t-test between upright and inverted faces conditions (as used in the power analysis). We expect the difference in blurriness to baseline is significantly higher in the upright than in the inverted condition.

Group 2: partial blurriness range

We will use two one-sample t-tests (one-tailed) for the blurriness level difference between baseline and memory phase, one for inverted and one for upright faces. For inverted faces the blurriness level will be significantly lower in memory than in baseline. For upright faces, we expect no significant differences between memory and baseline.
